Economia and Centrum connect management.
For example, they will offer joint advertising
New integrated newsroom of Economia in Prague's Karlín district.
Economia has taken another step in transforming the Centrum holding into its media house.
Since Friday, Economia and Centrum have shared top management.
"The unification of the organizational structure and the personnel union are essential for the integration of both publishers into a common media house," says Kamil Čermák, Vice-Chairman of the Board of Directors of Economia and Managing Director, commenting on the changes.
Čermák, who will head the unified management, will be joined by Centrum Holdings Executive Director Andreas Demuth.
Pavel Vopařil has been appointed as the new joint sales director, and Zuzana Tylčerová, the advertising director of both companies, is also subordinate to him.
Štěpán Burda became the new head of information technology.
The joint editorial director is Vladimír Piskáček, whose team also includes the director for transformation Jakub Unger.
Adéla Pittsová was entrusted with the newly established position of Marketing Director.
The independent Corporate Communications Department is now headed by Věra Lhotská.
The joint financial director is Karel Žalud, human resources management for both publishers is led by Petra Slabá.
"The new organizational structure will allow us, among other things, to come to the market with a common offer of advertising products, to better interconnect the content creation of all published titles and, last but not least, to significantly streamline the company's business management," added Čermák.
Economia, owned by financier Zdeněk Bakala, entered into an agreement to acquire Centrum Holdings and its Czech subsidiaries at the end of April.
Centrum Holdings' portfolio consists of Aktuálně.cz servers, Žena.cz, web portals, an extensive e-mail base under the Centrum.cz and Atlas.cz brands, and the Najisto SMB agency, and a portfolio of nearly twenty smaller websites.
Economia is the publisher of Hospodářské noviny, the IHNED.cz news server, the weekly magazines Respekt and Ekonom, and a number of printed and online B2B titles.
Among Czech publishers, it has long been the most successful in selling digital versions of its main titles.
In June this year, the publishing house moved to newly built modern premises in Prague's Karlín district.
CNN: Israel bombed a military base in Syria.
The target was supposed to be Russian missiles for Hezbollah.
Israeli warplanes reportedly bombed a military base near the Syrian port of Latakia on Thursday.
Citing an unnamed U.S. government official, CNN reported.
The Israeli press widely reported on the explosion at the alleged rocket depot, but the attack on it was not confirmed by the Israeli government.
An Israeli military spokeswoman declined to comment on the airstrike when asked by CNN.
"We do not comment on foreign media reports," she said.
The target of the Israeli airstrike, according to a U.S. government source, were rockets and related equipment that the Israelis believe could be transported to the militant Lebanese Hezbollah movement.
The Associated Press, citing another U.S. security official, reported that Russian SA-125 missiles were the target of an Israeli airstrike on a target on Syrian territory.
A second channel of Israeli television reported that the target of the attack was allegedly a highly modern Syrian air defense system.
Satellite images of the attack area showed a battery of Russian S-125 Neva missiles, according to the DPA news agency.
In addition, they reportedly showed a battery of SA-3 missiles, including a command center with a radar to track missiles and their targets.
The missiles have a range of 35 kilometers and could carry warheads weighing 70 kilograms, according to an Israeli television report.
Israel has reportedly bombed rocket shipments inside Syria at least twice this year, CNN and AP reported.
The Israeli military has never responded to such reports, but has repeatedly said it will hit any arms shipment to Hezbollah or other groups designated as terrorists.
