The Brno Observatory will take visitors into space in a new digitarium
At first glance, it is obvious that the hall of the large planetarium has changed in the last six months.
There is a new stage, visitors can sink into new comfortable seats and a projection screen with a diameter of 17 meters in the shape of a dome from the American company Spitz has been added above their heads.
In the middle of the hall is its most important part, a new projector from Japan.
To make the picture perfect, other smaller projectors are scattered around the hall.
Another important part of the whole facility is hidden behind the walls of the hall.
"These are twenty-one computers that generate images," said Jiří Dušek, director of the Brno Observatory.
Computers ensure that the image from multiple projectors does not overlap, but gives a coherent impression.
"The performance of computers is thirty to forty times higher than that of conventional personal computers," said Tomáš Hladík, a technician from the observatory.
The digitarium can conjure up an extremely realistic and plastic model of the night sky, the human body or the ocean floor.
Viewers will find themselves right in the middle of the universe or the human brain.
Another similar facility is closest to Warsaw or Hamburg.
The management of the observatory plans to screen purchased programs and their own work in the hall.
From Saturday, there are two programs on the program.
The first is called Astronaut and is intended for adults.
People will learn about astronaut training, fly into space, spin on centrifuges, and then see the challenging conditions astronauts face in space.
The second show is for children and is called Magic Reef - Kaluoka'hina.
It tells the story of a reef whose colourful inhabitants lived a peaceful life until the moment when a nearby volcano erupted.
The entire digitarium cost about fifty million crowns, which was mainly paid by the Ministry of Education.
Smaller amounts were also contributed by the city of Brno and the observatory from their budget.
The projection screen cost ten million crowns, the projector twelve million.
"The rest was swallowed by audiovisual equipment and computers," Dusek explained.
The installation of the digitarium followed the reconstruction of the entire building, which the observatory underwent two years ago.
According to director Dušek, 25,000 to 30,000 visitors could come by the end of the year.
Supreme Court upholds Obama's health care bill
The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that the health care bill signed by Barack Obama is constitutional, a major victory for the Obama administration.
By a 5-4 vote, the court ruled that an individual regulation of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act – which requires citizens to purchase health insurance by 2014 or face a fine – does not contravene the Constitution under government tax power.
Chief Justice John Roberts sided with the four more liberal members of the court, while Justices Scalia, Thomas, Alito and Kennedy were in opposition.
The court also upheld the remaining parts of the 2700-page law and further ruled that a statutory health care requirement that directs states to expand the ability to obtain health insurance or risk losing all federal funding for health insurance is not coercive and inconsistent with the Constitution.
Lawsuits to block the law were filed by 26 states and the National Federation of Independent Enterprises.
During the 2012 primaries, the bill was vehemently opposed by every major Republican candidate, including presumptive nominee Mitt Romney.
