Egypt inaugurates the first freely elected president
Mohamed Morsi has been sworn in as an inaugural office, but his day of triumph is unlikely to end with political unrest in Egypt.
Mohamed Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he was inaugurated as the country's first freely elected president, after Hosni Mubarak, who had been ousted 16 months earlier.
At his inauguration before the High Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and Egypt's fifth head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took the oath before 18 judges dressed in black robes in a mansion built overlooking the Nile that resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are striving for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic," Morsi said at a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
"The Egyptian people today have laid the foundation of a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy and stability," said Morsi, a sixty-year-old US-trained engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been the target of fierce attacks by governments for most of the 84 years since its creation as an illegal organization.
When Morsi arrived shortly after 11 a.m. local time in a small motorcade, hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to celebrate the president, and contrary to the presidential pomp of the Mubarak era, traffic was only briefly halted to allow the motorcade to pass through the usually busy road connecting the city center with the suburbs to the south.
The personal prestige of Morsi, derisively described as the Muslim Brotherhood's uncharismatic "spare tire," has soared since his victory and his speech on Friday, which aimed to present him not only as an Islamist candidate, but also as a candidate for all those who want to see the revolt against the authoritarian Mubarak through to an end.
"Egypt today is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state," Morsi, dressed in a blue formal suit and red tie, told judges in the wood-paneled chamber where he was sworn in.
Morsi later traveled to Cairo University to deliver his inaugural address.
While standing at attention, he received an official welcome from a military band that played the national anthem.
Present was the military commander, Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi.
His arrival was accompanied by chants of "the army and the people are one hand" from hundreds of people gathered in the university's main lecture hall.
Cairo University was founded in 1908 as a center of secular education and later in the 70s became a bastion of Islamic student movements.
Morsi took a symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, the birthplace of the revolution that ended Mubarak's authoritarian rule last year, and vowed to reclaim presidential powers taken from office by the military council that had taken them from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to take an official oath in court, rather than before parliament, as is customary, he submitted to the will of the military, suggesting that the struggle for power will continue.
Morsi's speech in Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
