How they express their social status, what their tastes are.
And from the state of the graves, they will also find out how the survivors take care of their dead.
Halloween 2013: By the numbers
When I was little, Halloween was magical.
My sister and I could eat sweets, stay up late and show off to the neighbors in disguise.
Today I feel like I've become a scrooge.
For two years, there has been no candy in my apartment, and this year will probably be no different.
However, statistics show that I am the black sheep when it comes to Halloween.
According to the State Retail Federation (NRF), most Americans — 158 million of them, in fact — will celebrate Halloween this year, spending a total of $6.9 billion on sweets, costumes and ornaments.
But what I always look forward to on Halloween are trends.
According to the NRF, of the $6.9 billion spent, $1.2 billion is expected to go to costumes.
This year, the latest fad in fashion are sexy inanimate objects.
It's not just women who have to be sexy anymore; Foods like pizza, hamburger and carrots can also be sexy.
As for the men, I expect to see a lot of zombies thanks to the parade of the dead, and I bet the Daft Punk spacemen will make it to our Instagram feeds this year.
According to Google, the most searched costumes are zombies, Batman, pirates and witches.
I suppose there is nothing wrong with following tradition.
Last year we dressed our dogs in costumes and to my surprise we were not the only ones.
In fact, according to the NRF, Americans will spend $330 million this year on pet costumes.
So a lot of funny doggies will be seen.
When it comes to sweets, we don't waste time.
According to Nielsen, Americans will spend $1.9 billion.
That's roughly 300 million kg of Hershey bars, lollipops, Milk Duds and Twizzlers sweets, and Clark bars.
That's amazing news for the 41 million carolers who are about to raid our neighborhoods, according to the U.S. Department of Commerce.
In fact, on Halloween we buy, believe it or not, consume, 45 million kg of chocolate.
The only thing we don't want is corn candy, and yet nearly 16,000 tons of it are sold around Halloween, according to the National Candy Shop Association.
That's about 9 billion individual corn candies.
This is a mystery I have never solved.
Nothing is more typical of Halloween than haunted houses.
They have the best titles, like "Terror behind the walls", "Howl-O-Scream" and "The house of shock".
In fact, there are 1200 officially dedicated haunted houses in the United States that make a profit of $500 million according to American Haunted Houses, and that includes those amazing scared photos that your friend puts on Facebook and you can't remove them, and the person you like looks at the photo and comments like "you look nice."
And finally, a little about pumpkins.
When we were little, Charlie Brown introduced us to the Great Pumpkin, and carving a pumpkin lantern is like decorating a Christmas tree – we've been doing it since we were little.
Luckily for us, the "baby in pumpkin" trend only started last year thanks to Pinterest, so most of us grew up carving gourds instead of sitting in them.
This year, according to the U.S. Census Bureau, Americans will spend about $106 million on pumpkins.
The pumpkin lantern with a flickering flame on your front porch probably comes from Illinois, where 245,000 tons of pumpkins grew this year.
If you're looking for something extra, call Tim and Susan Mathisdon from Napa, California and try to cut up their pumpkin weighing almost one ton.
How insectoids from Thailand boosted sales of a Parisian bar
Maybe you scoff at insects and do not know that you eat about half a kilogram a year completely voluntarily.
For example, ground in flour.
If you consume it consciously, then you are clearly trendy: it is organic, nutritious and a unique experience is also taken care of.
The insect menu was first included in Paris on the menu of his business at the beginning of October by Elie Daviron, chef and owner of the bar Le Festin Nu.
The bar, whose name was inspired by William Burroughs' book The Naked Lunch, can be found in the trendy 18th district near Montmartre, frequented by tourists.
With fresh avocado, roasted red peppers, ginger and quail egg, guests can now bite not only various larvae, grasshoppers or water beetles, but also scorpions.
Carefully and specially packaged vans (so as not to damage the insects' wings, twist their legs or damage their eyes) are sent to the Davirons all the way from Thailand.
Europe is just learning to eat insects, elsewhere it is common.
The owner of a pioneering Parisian bar has a few reasons to eat insects.
The first is the environmental benefits, because the production of insects is much less expensive for our planet (in terms of finances, space and water consumption) than traditional meat.
"In addition, insects are an excellent source of protein and omega 3 fatty acids," Daviron told Reuters.
At the same time, the young chef does not deny his profession, simply aiming to offer his customers a unique culinary experience.
According to him, the right restaurant is the pleasure, the feeling of sin and the atmosphere of the environment.
"I'm not saving the world, I'm just mediating a new experience," he explained.
Not everyone would be excited about the idea of eating a beetle decorated with pesto, but the reaction of the customers of the Parisian bar to the insects served is very positive, according to the owner.
Even skeptics are said to eventually taste it, even if they start with the smallest bites and then choose a scorpion.
The prices of these tasting plates range from five to nine euros.
Do you wash your hands?
Scientists have found that washing your hands CHANGES YOUR MOOD.
The experiment involved 98 people, divided into three groups.
The first two were tasked with solving an impossible problem.
Of course, both failed.
But the group that washed its hands after the failure seemed much more optimistic than the one where the participants did not wash their hands.
The "hands washed" group also performed better than the other in the next test.
Still, those who washed their hands performed worse on subsequent tests than those who didn't.
The results of the "washed" were at the level of the third group, whose participants did not experience any previous failure.
According to psychologists, the results of the test show that physical cleanliness removes really negative feelings after failure.
At the same time, however, motivation decreases, the testers have to concentrate much more in the next exams.
If we transferred the results of the research to the Czechs, we would probably be the most optimistic after returning from the toilet.
After using the toilet, only one percent of Czechs do not wash their hands, but after traveling by public transport it is already a fifth.
They also usually stick to hygiene after working in the garden or in the workshop, when 85 percent of people wash their hands.
Caressing a pet motivates 78.7 percent of people to wash their hands.
A recent survey revealed that there is a difference in the perception of Czechs and Slovaks, how much it is necessary to wash their hands after shaking hands with a stranger.
In this situation, 28.8 percent of Czechs and 40.3 percent of Slovaks wash their hands.
The survey showed that both nations wash their hands about ten times a day.
"Although it would be appropriate, I am afraid that the reality is different and people are trying to do a little better," dermatologist Klaudie Komárková commented on the results of the survey.
A drug smuggling tunnel between the U.S. and Mexico with its own railroad has been found
One of the most sophisticated drug smuggling tunnels between the U.S. and Mexico has been discovered, complete with its own lighting, ventilation and electric railroad.
U.S. authorities have described the one-by-one-meter tunnel as one of the most sophisticated secret passages they have ever discovered.
The tunnel, which winds its way to the length of nearly six football fields, connects warehouses near Tijuana, Mexico, and San Diego, USA.
The area is full of vague warehouses where trucks can easily be hidden before they are loaded with drugs.
Authorities said the tunnel was closed before drugs could be delivered undetected.
Along with the discovery of the tunnel, authorities also seized eight and a half tons of marijuana and about 150 kilograms of cocaine, according to court records.
Three men who authorities say worked as drivers were charged with possession of marijuana and cocaine with intent to distribute them.
If convicted, they face prison sentences ranging from 10 years to life imprisonment.
In Nogales, Arizona, smugglers are breaking into extensive drainage channels.
The tunnel is the eighth largest corridor discovered in San Diego since 2006.
Some of the largest tunnels were discovered in October after a marijuana harvest in central Mexico, which poses the problem of drug cartels to get their products to consumers as quickly as possible.
In 2010, authorities found a 650-meter-long corridor equipped with tracks that led from the kitchen of a house in Tijuana to two warehouses in San Diego.
Are the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of bringing businesses together and defining what changes British entrepreneurs and job-creating companies want to see in their relationship with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey, asking leading UK business leaders about their views on Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov surveyed 1,000 business leaders representing UK businesses of all sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are now looking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and growing, while EU countries are stagnating.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than embroiled in the long and arduous process of reforming Europe's mysterious institutions.
When asked for their views on specific policy areas – from monopoly regulations to product laws – most entrepreneurs expressed the view that control of these core competences should be returned to Westminster.
There was widespread dissatisfaction with the single market, with entrepreneurs saying that the costs of Brussels regulations now outweighed the benefits of being part of the European business area – even 40 percent of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European companies, agreed.
Finally, our survey of business leaders revealed the most telling insight, which is that a clear majority wants Britain to seek treaty change and a relationship with the EU that should be based on trade, not politics.
The findings, shared by businesses of all sizes and major business groups, suggest that the business sector is pushing for "meaningful change" that will shift influence back to Britain.
The stakes are high – achieving treaty change and a better deal for Britain could mean a gain of up to 16% in a referendum vote to remain in the EU.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this poll shows that British business supports his plan to amend the terms of Britain's membership of the EU.
It also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to mark a significant shift from the current balance of power back to Britain.
A better deal for Britain is possible and, as the eurozone embarks on its way to closer economic and fiscal union, increasingly necessary.
Jobs and growth in Britain must be a priority and, as our survey results show, this means a renewed focus on trade and a fundamental change in Brussels' regulatory approach for business.
