The UK government has announced a study that aims to increase the benefits of the HS2 rail project for Scotland.
HS2's work suggests that high-speed services for Scotland and the north of England will start as soon as the first phase launches in 2026.
Transport Minister Baroness Kramer said the project would "bring the UK together".
Scottish Transport Secretary Keith Brown said he was "thrilled" to work with the British government on the plan.
The first phase will consist of a new high-speed train line between London and the West Midlands.
Upon completion of Phase Two, the service will run from Manchester to Leeds.
In June, the government revised the estimated cost of building a high-speed line between London and northern England from £32.7 billion to £42.6 billion.
The British government, which held talks with the national transport authority Transport Scotland, commissioned HS2 to explore additional rail capacity and the possibility of improving travel times for northern England and Scotland.
This includes the possibility of eventual travel times from Glasgow and Edinburgh to London equivalent to three hours or less.
Baroness Kramer said: "Our target for HS2 is really a national network that better connects the UK and its cities."
We gave SH2 the green light because the benefits it will bring are huge.
Without this, we face a crisis in the capacity of our rail network.
But it's also about connectivity – across the UK, HS2 will better connect 18 cities, including Glasgow and Edinburgh.
Scottish Minister Alistair Carmichael added: "Today's announcement is good news for Scotland."
On behalf of the Scottish Government, Keith Brown called on Mr Carmichael to "unequivocally" support Scotland's integration into the HS2 network.
Mr Brown said: "A high-speed line has the potential to bring immeasurable economic benefits to Scotland, but it also adds economic weight to Scotland in the overall high-speed rail case across Britain."
We are therefore keen to work with the UK Government to explore the possibility of bringing high-speed rail to Scotland to benefit everyone and complement the Glasgow-Edinburgh line, which the Scottish Government is planning to do anyway.
I look forward to reviewing the report on this study with British ministers over the next year and to deciding together on the next steps.
Frontier Airlines to Charge Hand Baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for carry-on baggage on board flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to introduce a fee of up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although they said in an announcement Wednesday that passengers would be allowed to keep the entire can.
The new carry-on baggage charge applies to baggage in the upper storage compartment, so small bags under the seat will continue to be free.
Frontier says it will charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if passengers wait until arriving at the gate to pay.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the hundred-dollar fee was meant to encourage passengers to pay in advance.
"We would not like to collect this fee," she said.
Airlines started charging for first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers tried to avoid these charges and stuffed as much as they could into hand luggage hidden in the storage compartment, so there was often no space in this space.
Fees are one way to teach passengers to take fewer things on board.
Ms O'Malley said the new fee was really not intended to raise more money.
The point is that Frontier's most loyal customers have made it very clear that finding space in the top storage compartment is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who purchase tickets on the airline's website will not pay.
This means that one passenger queuing at Frontier's gate can bring baggage for which they pay nothing, while the other passenger in the queue will pay $100 for the same baggage.
Ms O'Malley said the website and check-in procedures would be modified to ensure passengers were aware of the charge before they arrived at the gate.
Frontier's new carry-on baggage fee won't take effect until the summer, but a date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who request this service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the extra baggage fee as a sign that airlines are struggling to raise enough money to cover the cost of air traffic after years of losses.
However, most did not touch the fees for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines was the first to charge for hand baggage three years ago, and another low-cost airline, Allegiant Air, later followed suit.
The only airline that also has such charges is Hungary's Wizz Air, says air travel consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional charges.
In its December 2011 report, it estimated that Spirit's carry-on baggage fee would bring in $50 million annually.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently flew with Spirit and wondered what he saw at the gate when passengers encountered Spirit's unusual carry-on baggage fee.
"Getting on a plane was the smoothest I've ever seen in my flying career," he said.
I expected to see gnashing of teeth and arguments at the gate.
The plane was full, he said, "and boarding was instantaneous."
Frontier will also apply fees for coffee, tea, soda and juice, following Spirit's lead.
Frontier said passengers who receive soda or juice can keep the entire can and coffee will be replenished for free.
Water will continue to be served free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to introduce beverage charges in 2008, but backed down seven months later after passenger complaints and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier's latest move to charge for hand baggage if passengers don't buy a flight directly from the airline is its last effort to direct customers directly to its website.
Airlines pay online travel retailers like Orbitz between $10 and $25 for each ticket sold.
This has given all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy directly from them, instead of doing so through online travel agencies.
But Frontier has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, it began giving customers who made purchases through an online travel agency just half of its frequent flyer miles.
On Wednesday, it trimmed the reward for miles flown to 25 percent of the miles of the trip.
So a 1,000-mile trip with Frontier purchased through an online travel agency means a reward of 250 miles.
The company also allows customers to select their seat in advance only if they make a purchase directly through the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in its hometown of Denver, but its business is starting to shrink and it's losing money.
According to financial results reported Wednesday by corporate partner Republic Airways Holdings, sales fell 9 percent and transport capacity shrank nearly 13 percent in the first quarter
By selling the airline, Republic is also trying to solve Frontier's financial problems.
We studied 11 THOUSAND ADS!
We know where they want you to work!
In November last year, the analysis detected over 11,000 job advertisements, of which 4300 were published in the daily press and 6800 ads (62 percent) on the Internet.
The Internet is therefore becoming the most important medium for posting job offers.
In 2005, when the survey was first conducted, its share was 26 percent.
In the last two surveys (2007, 2010) it stabilized at about 60 percent.
According to the analysis, job advertisements largely reflect the current situation on the labour market.
An example can be a simple comparison of the number of published advertisements in the period of economic prosperity and in the time of economic crisis.
For example, in 2007, almost 25 900 advertisements were published in the same reporting period, in 2012 it was less than half.
The offer of jobs on the Internet is oriented to a narrower, especially more qualified group of professions.
On the other hand, the offer of employment in the daily press covers a wider range of professions, including blue-collar professions, said the author of the analysis, Pavlína Šťastnová.
The level of representation of selected professional groups varies for both media.
On the Internet, advertisements looking for managers and executives, sales representatives, programmers and financial experts took a prominent place.
Positions of programmers or small business leaders were only on the Internet.
In the daily press, the share of these professional professions is significantly lower, while a large representation belongs mainly to service and manual professions.
One of the most frequently mentioned requirements that employers express through advertising offers is, of course, education.
Other monitored areas included knowledge of foreign languages, especially English.
In the daily press, the requirement for knowledge of a foreign language was mentioned in three percent of advertisements, on the Internet in 37 percent.
