Indeed, demand across Southeast Asian regions – where household debt is rising – is such that ValueMax, where a woman makes her transaction, became the third pawnshop on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Pawning jewellery is not only a quick way to borrow cash – SGD1300 in the case of Ms Amirthalinga – but is also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Pawnshops in Singapore routinely apply an annual percentage rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent rate offered by United Overseas Bank, a local bank with a branch in the same shopping mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require verification of a person (payment history) or proof of income, and can make a loan faster than banks.
And so, as families feel the pressure from the rising cost of living and rising household and consumer debt, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops.
After five years of massive growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit fueled by loose monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to deal with a deteriorating financial situation.
This week, rating agency Standard & Poor's cited the increasing use of credit in households, mainly due to rising rents, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
She said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in terms of gross domestic product.
Malaysia tops the list with a ratio of 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists were also worried about high levels of consumer debt in Thailand, which barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
