George Kerevan: A divided Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another scary story about independence.
This time there is a warning that a condition for an independent Scotland's membership in the EU would be its entry into Schengen.
This gave rise to stories of passport control at Berwick and the barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
It is true that the Strathclyde newspaper mentioned the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but – predictably – this did not make headlines.
Nobody has also mentioned that EU Member States spend a lot of time adapting their official laws when it suits them.
Given that Scotland is not now in Schengen, offering continued discord would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for anything they really want from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
And so old that it became an excavation. I heard the journalistic canard that "independence means passport control" at least 40 years ago.
Still, there is an interesting idea hidden in this bearded tale.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to obey Europe at all?
Why swap the London chomout for the Brussels one, especially now?
This is the real European story: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
Due to the euro crisis, the so-called Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties dedicated to opposing the EU or abolishing the euro as a common currency are gaining influence.
Even in Germany, the euroskeptic Alternative for Germany party – founded this year – came out of nowhere and captured nearly five million votes in September's federal election, effectively "sweeping" the Free Democrats (the equivalent of Britain's Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
At home, there has always been opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a decisive moment.
The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, together with the straitjacket put on national economies through adherence to the common currency, has led many to believe that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running large budget deficits – this was true only in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a euro system that locks its members into exchange rates favorable to German exporters – something that German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the domestic currency, southern Europe has a disadvantage compared to Germany in terms of domestic production.
The only help is to cut revenues and public spending – as Germany is urging to do.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies the deeper cause of Europe's languid performance.
As a result of the "green" energy policy promoted by Brussels – a code to support French and German companies at the consumer's expense – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gasoline as it does in the United States.
This is a paralyzing cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
All the world's wage freezes would not avert trampling Europe's petrochemical industry with cheap shale oil from the US.
The result is a smouldering rebellion, especially in France, once an enthusiastic supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool that would rein in Germany and allow Paris to put itself on a par with Washington in the world.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a token of political legitimacy, and has imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving France's worn-out economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right wing, the anti-EU National Front, has just won a major by-election, relegating the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France, with 24% of the vote – an early warning to British Labour that they cannot assume that splits on the right will automatically have a positive effect on the left.
How does Le Pen deal with her newfound popularity among the white working class?
She would like to use next year's European elections to create an anti-European bloc across the European Parliament against the common currency.
If anti-EU parties do well in this election, as is likely, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time in history.
It occurs to me that in the foreseeable future the growing anti-European feeling and anti-common currency will come together and kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but will rather transform itself into something looser in the sense of the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project and align itself with the United States.
But Washington's increased interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
And where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be an area (basically) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – this includes the ability to tell Berlin and Brussels when to leave us alone.
I suppose Scotland would do well in Europe's loose arrangement, provided it retained its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should take the example of Norway and retain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – oddly enough – the most successful non-austerity political movement in Europe, winning by a large majority in 2011 thanks to an opposition to austerity planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the subsequent coalition of Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ridiculous if Scotland now voted for independence only to accept austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
