Karel Drábek: Uhlířský vrch - one of our youngest volcanoes.
Uhlířský vrch is a prominent hill 3 km southeast of Bruntál.
Together with several others, it is evidence of volcanic activity in Nízký Jeseník in recent times (from the geological point of view).
The last eruptions were still at the beginning of the Quaternary.
When viewed from a greater distance, the white plastered Baroque pilgrimage church of Our Lady of Help, built in 1755 - 1765, is conspicuous at the top of Uhlířský vrch.
It replaced the original wooden pilgrimage chapel.
The inn, which stood next to the church, has not been preserved.
Shortly after the completion of the church, an alley of four rows of linden trees, about 1 km long, was planted.
The Stations of the Cross on Uhlířský vrch are the third version, the original one stood here after 1916, the second, from 2001, lasted only until 2004.
At fifteen stations there are wooden sculptures made by the local artistic woodcarver František Nedomlel.
He used various species of trees from the area of Nízký Jeseník.
Similarly, pedestals made of rocks from the area form an interesting geological exposition.
At each stop, the name of the sponsor is also listed.
Uhlířský vrch is a remnant of a young volcano.
Although radiometric age measurements vary slightly, the last eruption was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is therefore younger than Velký Roudný (3.3 million years old) and older than the Venus volcano (0.8 million years old).
The volcano was born by an explosion.
It ejected a considerable amount of volcanic ash along with rock fragments from the bedrock, which acquired a reddish-brown color when burned.
At the end of this phase, lava flowed to the surface - today it is a layer of porous basalt up to 13 meters thick.
The second eruption ejected red, brown-red and sometimes black tuffs.
Their layer is up to 50 meters thick and part of it is accessible in the quarry wall.
In the tuffs are conspicuous volcanic bombs up to 1 meter in size.
At the end of the activity, lava flowed from the volcano, which today forms a layer of slag basalt up to 50 m thick.
Volcanoes, where volcanic ash eruptions alternate with lava flows, are the most common type of volcanoes.
Because they are actually composed of layers, they were called stratovolcanoes.
The original volcanic cone gradually underwent erosion.
However, it was threatened by rock mining in the quarry on the south side.
The most intensive mining took place here in the years 1953 - 1962.
Tuffs were added to concrete, which was then lighter and had better thermal insulation properties.
Mining was stopped under pressure from experts and the public and thus preserved this unique place.
However, the problem is in the porosity and small cohesion of the rocks, which quickly weather, disintegrate and slide down the slope.
The quarry is disappearing relatively quickly.
To complicate matters further, the warm, south-facing slope is an ideal place for some rare species of flora and fauna.
Correction is therefore problematic, but over time it will be necessary to select and maintain a characteristic geological profile.
This is nothing new, similar profiles are maintained in a number of important locations.
You can get to Uhlířský vrch by following the green tourist trail from Bruntál or from Slezský Kočov.
Motorists can use the free parking lot at the beginning of the linden alley, where a short nature trail begins.
