On Thursday, the decline was 39 cents, falling 5.8 percent for the month of October.
Abundant oil reserves have weighed on the price in recent weeks.
The Energy Department said Wednesday that U.S. inventories have increased by 4.1 million barrels in the past week.
In five weeks, inventories increased by more than 25 million barrels.
On Friday, however, two reports of Chinese manufacturing gave rise to more demand, which showed growth in activity.
This suggests that China's economic recovery could continue to strengthen after growth that rebounded to 7.8 percent in the third quarter after two weak decades.
Brent crude, a measure for international crude also used by U.S. refineries, fell 26 cents to $108.58 a barrel on the International Trade Exchange in London.
