Scientists have shed more light on how tail movements are related to the mood of the dog
Previous research has shown that joyful dogs wag their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs swing their tails mostly to the left.
But now scientists say other dogs can spot and respond to these subtle differences in tail movement.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trento, said: "It is well known in humans that the left and right sides of the brain have different links to stimuli that trigger positive or negative emotions."
We tried to observe the same in other species.
He added that, as in humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa in dogs, and that the two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
In an effort to learn more about how dogs react to the asymmetrical wagging of other dogs' tails, the researchers monitored animals that watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side, and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs films about dogs – either in natural or silhouette form – to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we were also able to adjust the movement of the tail to show it more to the right or left."
When the animals saw an otherwise featureless dog move its tail to the right (from the point of view of a dog wagging its tail), it remained completely calm.
But when she noticed the tail turning mostly to the left (again from the point of view of a dog wagging its tail), their heart rate increased and the animals looked insecure.
Professor Vallortigara said he doesn't think dogs consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they must and must not pay attention to.
He said: "If you encounter dogs several times and the movement of their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with more friendly behaviour, and movement to the right breeds less friendly behaviour, you will react based on that experience."
The researchers say the findings can help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their pets' emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a university lecturer in veterinary medicine at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right sides were important for dogs.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they observe an aggressive dog, and to the right when looking at a cheerful dog.
And in another paper from Victoria University in Canada, he said: "Dogs were more likely to become familiar with robot dogs when they wag their tails to the left than to the right, when they became insecure – exactly the opposite of the Italian study."
The difference, he said, may be that the dogs in these various studios didn't interpret the animals in the movies or the robot dogs entirely as dogs.
He explained that a study on how dogs react to real dogs could help.
"Although in the case of many different mammals there is strong evidence that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won't be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
RBS suspends two foreign exchange traders
According to two people familiar with the situation, the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) is suspending two traders in its foreign exchange division, another indication that global investigations by regulators into suspected currency market manipulation are becoming more frequent.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with authorities to investigate the world's largest financial market, where $5.3 trillion changes hands every day.
The two traders would be the first RBS employees suspended as part of a widening investigation in response to the LIBOR (London Interbank Interest Rate) scandal.
The bank declined to comment on the suspensions but confirmed that it had received a request for information from authorities this month.
"Our ongoing investigation into this matter continues and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and our other authorities," the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, people close to the incident said RBS had passed to the UK's Financial Conduct Authority records of emails and instant messages sent to and from the former trader's accounts.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and is believed to have been released from his current position as European Chair of Foreign Exchange Trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, Citi's European chairman of cash trading, went on leave this week, while Matt Gardiner, former head of currency trading at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
Neither of these traders was charged with any offence.
Mr. Usher's instant messaging group included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, people familiar with the incident said.
UBS said this week that it had taken action against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finma announced it had investigated suspicious foreign exchange market machinations at several Swiss banks.
Worldwide, at least six authorities – the European Commission, Finma, Switzerland's antitrust authority Weko, FCA, the US Department of Justice, and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are investigating claims that these bankers colluded to move the currency market.
People familiar with the situation said HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse had also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from the relevant authorities.
Banks scour through years-old instant messages and emails to find cases of violations.
News of the investigations has alarmed traders in an area that has been one of the biggest engines of profit generation in investment banks' closures in recent years, but which has been hampered by the fact that low currency volatility has limited opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the situation, arguing that the vast and highly liquid foreign exchange market is virtually impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say this is not necessarily true.
A senior trader said that despite the significant volume of daily foreign exchange trading, the slicing of liquidity between different trading platforms and banks increasing the use of their own internal platforms means that "you can start to influence the market at relatively low prices."
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced that it had fired from its stock trading department this week a trader who caused a loss of nearly $6 million late last year.
The Bank immediately alerted the relevant authorities and cooperates with their supervisory authorities.
"We believe that this trader acted alone and that this issue has been resolved," Credit Suisse said.
