After many years of reading, living but not writing, VÁCLAV KAHUDA (1965) publishes a new novel Vítr, tma, přítomnost.
That it will not be a slim volume is suggested by the number of pages comparable to his best-known work, The Thicket (Petrov, 2001).
For Salon Kahuda interviewed another prominent contemporary Czech writer - Emil Hakl.
What moved you to write a novel after twelve years of silence?
I did it - so as not to choke on hatred.
To see around him more and more clones of this human foolish pettiness, young organisms afflicted by blind selfish efforts.
I'm not even talking about us elders, faces ruined by helpless lust, scoundrel souls and oppositely reversed ideologues who try to sell their "product" with the expression of a small whore.
At the beginning of the millennium, I bought a small digital camera and filmed my squeamish friends, weirdos and hidden formations.
I've gotten over it.
Sometimes I feel my brain burning from living on this planet.
I prefer to go for walks and then read books by the lamp in the evening.
You talk about a sense of frustration, hatred.
Was there a turning point somewhere in the past that affected you, or are you just getting older, like all of us?
The turning point came a long time ago, when I was about ten years old.
It didn't have a name then.
Well, and after that I lived.
But somewhere inside, there's still a surprised quiet boy.
I see other solitary exercisers, each in their tornado of anguish.
Writing books saved me.
I am participating in this huge, thousand-year-long movement of the system of life on this planet - the birth of an elusive future.
The immense, breathtaking complexity of life, where every stone is a direct heir of our presence.
We are players of a sad and beautiful game, where through trial and error more and more generations of beings are created, creating some superhuman, artificial intelligence in trillions of interactions per second.
Twelve years is a relatively long time.
Do you see your writing as an ongoing process, or did you start from scratch?
Self-talk, or rather dialogue, conducted by the right and left halves of the brain, sometimes floats to the surface and forms into a book.
Just as periods of peace are interwoven with quietly dormant metastases of wars that may one day awaken - so my book is twelve years of silence clothed in words.
I felt a mute avalanche of life growing in my brain, and if I didn't do anything, it would one day quietly overwhelm me.
It is a set of questions formulated by the brain and asked to layers that are stored in the darkness "below the surface of consciousness."
The neocortex, the grey matter of the brain, asks older evolutionary formations, goes to the ancient rings of the brain tree.
He speaks to furry beasts, asks snakes, looks for an answer in the flight of birds, raises his gaze to the clouds in the sky.
Yes, the moral law in me and the starry sky above me.
Finally, the brain asks the world.
You often talk about the ego metaphorically – could you define it biologically?
The brain stores in its billions of connections and electrochemical connections all the memories, experiences and experiences that the person has experienced.
This forest of logically and emotionally exposed and branching trees of information, registers of memory, uses the brain in its cognitive, cognitive, process, being exposed to an ever-changing present, in a constant effort to name and understand its surroundings and decode important messages.
Sometimes overload failures occur.
By analogy - as if your PC "crashed", from a speech emulator and translator program from foreign languages, you would get tangled first in the operating environment, such as Windows, and after several unsuccessful reboots you ended up at the dark green flickering screen of the Bios, in the base system that controls functions and cooperation on the motherboard, between the processor and the operating memory, etc.
For those who have not yet understood what we are talking about, I am talking about a psychospiritual crisis.
You mention it often - why are you regularly interested in this type of regression?
Because it's a pit.
In the hitherto functional mechanisms of our thinking, feeling and behavior - a rift appears.
Here it is good to quote Nietzsche: "So long did he look into the abyss until the abyss looked into him."
A genuine feeling - that a person is lost, if all hope disappears, he mentally "dies" and a new quality begins.
And why am I personally interested?
I will answer with a parable.
Once upon a time one fell into a pool and drowned, the days, months and years passed, he was always drowning while reading, and those books taught him to swim - that is, to live.
He became a "diver".
Perhaps a sentence written by me will help someone, as Hrabal's texts once helped me.
To what extent do you think of the reader, of the specific person who will read your text?
The one about whom nothing meaningful can be said, some call it consciousness, others super ego, but I think Arthur Rimbaud best characterized it in a letter to a friend:
"I'm someone else – this reader is directly involved in the process of formulating words and sentences."
From an early age he read books of old Czech fairy tales, sailed in Captain Nemo's submarine, ran around Stínadly in dark streets.
In the end, behind all the branching of the authors and their message, it is: "The Sun Bright of the Worlds of Other Worlds by Karel Hynek Mácha".
And when the book is out?
Do you care about the reader's opinion?
On the feedback that gets to you through the people who read the book?
Of course, I care about the opinion of people who take three hundred crowns and are willing to read five hundred pages of text.
And then, perhaps years later, they randomly contact me on the street and thank me for helping them with my book in some of their difficult life decisions.
Books are really "lives," or rather "worlds."
They are encoded in the signs of letters, they carry experience, the history of the regions of a particular language.
We can bring them to life at any time by letting their sentences flow to the brain.
It is actually, in a way, something forbidden divine - to awaken more and more life stories, small universes and temporary planets.
It is a fact whose DNA is stored in lines - according to ancient demonological books, we are committing witchcraft.
After the publication of the book - as it happens - a chain of author readings awaits you.
I remember you once liked to read.
Will you throw yourself into it again with joy, or do you feel differently after years?
Today, I prefer to just talk.
And what did I find out in the process?
There are good, intelligent people everywhere.
Their basic feature - they are inconspicuous, do not draw too much attention to themselves, have a friendly radiance, you do not feel lonely with them.
Let me give you an example - in the town of Červený Kostelec there lived (and I hope he still lives) a curly-haired bookseller (his name is aptly Červenka), a cheerful companion and a good girl's bull.
During one drink, he introduced me to the individual links in the chain of readers of my book The Thicket.
I looked into their eyes, and then was shown a tattered, worn copy of my book.
Embarrassed, I put down the sausage I had just read and wept briefly in a masculine manner.
We all stood there in silence, swaying and drunkenly in tears.
Then the young blond half-breed couldn't stand it and roared headfirst out of the window into the snowdrift.
It was on the ground floor.
We ran out into the night landscape and, caught up in the happy rabies of the sensitives, the aching soul of our compatriots and the nostalgia of the forgotten patriots - howled and brayed like werewolves until morning.
Each of your books is formally and content-wise different from the previous ones.
Is this also true of the text Wind, Darkness, Presence?
It's a narrative.
It is a fairy tale about one country beyond nine rivers and nine mountains.
Ivan Bunin, in his novel Sukhodil, puts the words of an old Russian myth into the mouth of a folk healer: On the sea, on the ocean, on the island of Bujan.
Lies a dog, on it a gray chest.
Horror, horror, mystery.
It's never happened, but we all know it from somewhere.
Perhaps once upon a time we were devils in hell and drew lots - what role will we play on this earth.
Are you going to keep writing, or are you going to leave it to the free flow of inspiration again?
The answers are eternal - Otokar Březina.
Writing is a wonderful way of dialogue.
Something huge and unnameable, similar to the movement of the continents on the planet, influences our volition from such a depth and in such a breadth that it completely exceeds our horizon - and so we act with absolute certainty exactly in line with our programmed assignment.
We are rewarded with an influx of dopamine, a mixture of endorphins and other substances.
We are biological machines.
We want to mate, we die defending and gaining new personal territories.
Sometimes a disorder happens and we radiate compassion.
Only then do we have the right to call ourselves human.
This is the answer to your question - the biological robot is already full of various disorders, standing on the shore of the ocean of unconsciousness and catching tides of warm wind in a leaky sail made of dirty handkerchief.
I have to write to be human.
Schools should focus more on math, spelling and grammar
English literature classes will require at least one Shakespeare play, a 19th-century novella, romantic poetry, and contemporary British fiction from 1914 onwards.
The exam will also include "hidden text" to motivate deeper reading;
Combined courses in English literature and language will be cancelled.
From 2015, students will be required to take a baccalaureate in a language and will be encouraged to choose English literature as an elective subject.
The Ministry of Education is expected to release a new curriculum for English and maths tomorrow – the first subjects to undergo radical change.
For other key subjects, changes are expected next year.
In a separate move, Ofqual, which oversees GCSEs, will reveal changes in the structure of GCSEs, along with a new grading system and a smaller volume of projects for students.
In a speech in the summer, Education Secretary Michael Gove said there was "a broad consensus on whether we need to reform our exam system to regain the trust of society" and that there was a need to insist that GCSEs be "more demanding, more ambitious and more rigorous".
The study shows that English schools devote less time to maths – 116 hours a year or three hours a week – than most other countries.
By comparison, schools in Australia devote an average of 143 hours a year to mathematics and about 138 in Singapore.
While there will be no official requirement to devote more time to math, coalition sources said a comprehensive GCSE in mathematics – along with a greater emphasis on the subject on leaderboards – is likely to encourage schools to provide extra tuition.
The curriculum will focus more on "real-world problems," including financial mathematics.
Mayor of Ostrava Kajnar: I am not cancer in ČSSD
Before the elections, a long-simmering dispute between two wings fighting for influence within the Ostrava ČSSD flared up.
Everything culminated when the Mayor of Ostrava, Petr Kajnar, turned to the court for the undemocratic composition of candidates.
Despite this, the participants in the case did not want to comment too much on this, so as not to damage the party even more before the elections.
But now the votes are counted.
The leadership of Ostrava's ČSSD called on the mayor of Ostrava to leave the party on Monday evening and will probably push for him to lose his position.
But Petr Kajnar wants to fight on.
What the disputes are about and who is on whose side, he described in an exclusive interview for Deník.
How do you perceive the outcome of the elections?
The CSSD certainly counted on a much better result.
Was it damaged by the fact that disputes within the party were being resolved in the media before the elections?
I can imagine that the Social Democrats could have had a better election result.
But on the other hand, it corresponds to the state in which the ČSSD is now.
It is a party that has its internal problems, it is internally ill, and people perceive that all is not well in it.
They made that clear in the election.
What are the internal diseases of ČSSD?
In my opinion, the ODS has been going through a decline for some time now, and unfortunately similar things are happening in the Social Democrats now.
It is so that lobbyists, influential people who previously expected to find their prebends in the ODS, have moved to the people in the ČSSD and have influence on them.
It is then related to the fact that the police walk around the offices of the Ostrava City Hall and collect computers.
It shows that ČSSD is not only composed of people who would like the good of everyone else, but many of them think primarily of their own good.
The ČSSD is divided into two irreconcilable camps in Prague as well, as can be seen in the current power struggle between the Haškovec and Sobotkovci.
But even that has been in the works for a long time.
What happened before the elections in Ostrava was only a foretaste of what is happening now in Prague.
Hašek's wing gradually occupied positions so that after the elections it could create a situation that would weaken Sobotka's wing.
One is in a situation in politics where one sometimes has to make compromises.
But everyone has an internal boundary where it is no longer possible to make compromises, and this is also my case.
Originally, I did not want to run for the Chamber of Deputies, but when I perceived the whole thing inside the party, I agreed with Luboš Zaorálek that I would try to get on the regional list in order to strengthen Sobotka's wing as the mayor of Ostrava.
But Hašek's wing put a stop to it.
Why do you stand on the side of Bohuslav Sobotka and not Michal Hašek?
In my opinion, Slávek Sobotka is a person who always talks primarily about the ČSSD program and, to a certain extent, about visions for the party and for this country.
I confess that I have not heard anything like that from the other side.
Michal Hasek is just fighting for power.
I do not understand how the Presidium, which is a lower body than the Central Executive Committee, can start just dismissing the Party Chairman.
This is a struggle for power regardless of everything and against the party statutes.
In my opinion, what Michal Hašek has now done in Prague has ended his political career.
How did you perceive the fact that the Ostrava leadership of the ČSSD did not approve you as a candidate?
Political parties are based on a competition to see who will place among their members.
The competition should be largely based on program visions and the ability of those people to fulfill those visions.
Of course, this competition is also entered by people who do not have much ability or vision, but a political party is an elevator for them to money that they would not get elsewhere.
The problem is when these people come to the fore by unscrupulously breaking the rules, violating the party statutes.
With their practices, they turn political parties into mafias, and in my opinion, they also violate the laws of the Czech Republic.
Drawing attention to this problem is more important to me than taking into account whether a Kajnar has a political future.
It is important that the parties start respecting the statutes.
That is why, before the elections, you filed a petition with the court for a preliminary injunction against the form of the ČSSD candidate list in the Moravian-Silesian Region?
The current ČSSD District Executive Committee in Ostrava is consolidating its power by being able to abolish organizations that do not suit it, purposefully establishing new organizations, gradually throwing out inconvenient party members.
An example is that they wanted to expel Richard Bednařík from the club of representatives, but he filed a lawsuit against it and they then rather canceled the resolution on his expulsion.
This shows that demanding compliance with the party's statutes through the courts is indeed the last resort, but at the moment when the other methods and control bodies within the ČSSD have ceased to function, it is the only option.
The leadership of the Ostrava ČSSD, headed by MP Adam Rykala, is trying to remove you from the position of mayor.
It is an open secret that the mayor of Poruba, Lumír Palyza, is interested in this post.
That's right, Adam Rykala and Lumír Palyza are trying to do everything they can to dismiss me.
They promise people positions, get votes, and in return for those votes, they consolidate their power in the party.
When I go back to the past, everything that happened around the Baník Ostrava football club and the purchase of the Bazaly stadium was just an excuse for them to attack me.
It was artificially staged so that they could label me as a person who puts money where it does not belong.
At the same time, the city bought property that is of great strategic value to it.
So how do you see it going on with your continued presidency as mayor?
The district committee has already called on me and other people on Monday to consider remaining in the ČSSD.
But I think it's like a thief shouting, "Catch the thief!"
When we look at the results of my work over the past eleven years, I do not see anyone in the Ostrava Social Democrats who would initiate and promote, sometimes even against party members, the creation of so many development issues, such as industrial zones or the expansion of the science and technology park.
Despite all this, I become uncomfortable.
I don't read it other than that I'm preventing others from breaking through to the places they want.
Will you continue to fight against these efforts?
Because if this republic is to function well, political parties must also work well.
I find it hard to believe that any party will be able to effectively manage the state if it cannot even manage itself.
So I'm not thinking about leaving the ČSSD now, because I think that the person causing the cancer of this party is not me, but these people who are trying to me off.
