John Kerry admitted: Spying has gone too far!
The United States has sometimes gone "too far" in spying, US Secretary of State John Kerry admitted during a video conference between Washington and London.
However, according to the minister, the collection of information served to avert terrorist attacks.
The "first admission from Washington" was made amid fierce controversy on both sides of the Atlantic over scandalous revelations about mass surveillance of data by the US National Security Agency (NSA), which also targeted US allies.
"In some cases, I concede, as the president (Barack Obama has done), some of these actions have gone too far, and we make sure that doesn't happen in the future," Kerry said.
In the interview, however, he mainly defended the existing practice.
According to him, the collection of information is necessary to combat terrorism and prevent assassinations such as the attacks of September 11, 2001 in the US, the attacks in Madrid in March 2004 or the London attacks in July 2005.
"We prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to be informed of the plots in a timely manner," Kerry said.
However, he again admitted that the collection of information "in some cases went disproportionately far".
The U.S. intelligence scandal, which reportedly tracked hundreds of millions of phone calls, erupted in Europe this month.
Among other things, it turned out that the Americans were also tracking the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
European leaders did not hide their indignation, with some calling on the European Union to try to reach an agreement with the United States that would prohibit or significantly restrict surveillance.
The Royal Commission learned that two employees of the Young Men's Christian Association (YMCA) had been charged before the charges against Jonathan Lord
The Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse has learned that before charges were brought against child educator Jonathan Lord of Caringbah in 2011, two employees of the Young Men's Christian Association (YMCA) in New South Wales had been charged with child sexual abuse.
But it was said before the commission that in its opening statement to the commission, the association said that they had never dealt with a child sexual abuse case in their organization.
Executive Director Phillip Hare was asked about a case in which a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offenses, and another in which a YMCA Caringbah gym teacher was convicted in 1991 of sexually molesting children in his care.
Mr Hare told Gail Furness, an adviser to the commission, that he knew about the first case but not about the second.
He admitted that the YMCA's introductory statement was also inaccurate when it stated that external audits were conducted at the YMCA to honor the organization as a leading advocate for children's rights.
The evidence presented by the commission suggests that the YMCA was alerted to having received the second lowest of the four possible ratings in an audit by the Ministry of Education and Society in August of this year.
Mr Hare, who joined the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that the downward leadership failed to hire Mr Lord without making sure staff were aware of the obligation to report child safety violations.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexually molesting 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was imprisoned for at least six years.
Mr Hare dismissed claims that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented staff from reporting breaches of child safety by Mr Lord.
Members of staff gave evidence that they witnessed such breaches, including Lord being alone with the children, babysitting them privately, letting them sit on his lap, telling them he loved them and letting them play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, who was Lord Lord's subordinate and asked for child safety training because she was concerned about his behaviour, testified that Jacqui Barnat, head of child services at the YMCA in Caringbah, who was Lord ́s supervisor, was "very intimidating and often difficult to talk to."
The CEO said he did not accept evidence from staff that they felt uncomfortable contacting their superiors and reporting the crimes.
Instead, he said that their friendship with Lord clouded their judgment, which is why they did not report the problem.
Mr Hare said he had given the YMCA board in New South Wales his view that the lesson of the "Jonathan Lord case" for the organisation was that staff had "not reported" and the board agreed with him.
Mr. Hare said the decision to have staff sign non-disclosure agreements shortly after the allegations emerged was made by YMCA general manager for children's services, Liam Whitley.
He said the aim was to avoid tampering with the evidence, but it was "overzealous" and poorly executed.
Child sexual abuse expert Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University told the commission that the YMCA in New South Wales was not a child-safe organisation between 2009 and 2011.
He said there were serious problems in recruitment, screening, training, training and staff management.
The hearing was adjourned to December 20.
