FAA: Air passengers can now use technological advances on planes (but not make calls from their cell phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their door-to-gate electronic devices — in addition to making calls from their mobile phones — to read, play games, watch movies and listen to music under eagerly awaited new rules released by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect the changes to happen immediately.
How quickly the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new rules and that they have updated cabin crew training manuals and storage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on planes.
Among the companies that have already handed over plans are Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the status of such a plan, we can improve the widespread use of electronic devices very quickly," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors close.
They cannot turn them on until the plane reaches a height of 3 kilometers and the captain gives permission.
Passengers are expected to turn their devices off again when the aircraft is descending to land and not to turn them on until the aircraft is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose planes are properly protected against electronic jamming can allow their passengers to use their devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified so that passengers can use Wifi at higher altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Stewards Association, welcomed the changes.
"Once the new rules are safely implemented – and we will work closely with transport companies on this – it will be a success," Glading said in a statement.
Frankly, we are tired of looking like "watchmen".
However, surfing the internet, sending emails and texts, and downloading data will still be prohibited below 3 kilometers of altitude, the agency said.
Passengers will be told to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still no Words with friends, the online scrabble game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when, as is well known, he was thrown off an American Airlines plane because he refused to turn off his device when the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will still have to be stored for fear that they could hurt someone if they fly around the cabin.
Calls from mobile phones will continue to be prohibited on board.
The rules for the use of mobile phones are not set by the FAA, but by the US Federal Telecommunications Commission.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the State Transportation Safety Committee, a national traffic safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones continue to be considered a risk.
"Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigation devices, but we also know from FCC data that they can cause interference to broadcast towers in the air," Rosenker said.
A industry advisory committee created by the FAA to investigate the issue suggested last month that the government allow the wider use of electronic devices.
The FAA has been pressured in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Sen. Claire McCaskill, a Democrat from Missouri, say there is no valid safety case for the ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of such devices is ubiquitous.
Some studies suggest that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the obligation to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to interference with navigation and communications equipment when passengers began carrying FM radios, a technical achievement of the time.
The new airlines are much more reliant on electrical systems than previous generation aircraft, but they are also designed, and approved by the FAA, to be resistant to electronic interference.
For several years, airlines have offered passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruising altitudes.
Plans modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airlines should adapt to greater use of electronic devices under the new rules, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much less intense radio transmissions than previous generation devices.
For example, e-readers emit only minimal broadcasts when turning a page.
But the broadcast is stronger when devices download or send data.
Among those pushing for restrictions on the use of these devices by passengers to be relaxed is Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of this company loaded the airliner with their electronic Kindle readers and conducted a test flight, but no problem appeared.
Members of the FAA's advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about whether these devices pose any risks.
Douglas Kidd, of the National Airline Passenger Association, said he believes interference from these devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee have said that there are only fragmentary reports from pilots to support the fact that such devices can cause interference with aviation systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off the device while flying by instrument in low visibility.
The travel industry group welcomed the changes and said it was a sensible practice for the travelling public, who are using the technology extensively.
"We are pleased that the FAA has recognized that a pleasant travel experience is not contrary to safety," said Roger Dow, executive director of the American Travel Association.
