For the words "Mugabe is a limp donkey" there is no longer a threat of imprisonment, the court struck down the law
Until now, Zimbabweans have had to be careful about speaking in public about eighty-nine-year-old Mugabe, who has ruled the country since the early 80s and has led the country since late 1987.
Under Section 33 of the Penal Code, disparaging the presidency was punishable by a fine of $100 to one year in prison.
"Public prosecutors should not be eager to accuse people who comment on the president in pubs or other public places," the Constitutional Court said.
Nine judges unanimously agreed that the law undermines freedom of expression.
It is likely that the government will appeal the court's decision, the BBC reported.
A number of aggrieved Zimbabweans have spoken out against the law, including Tendai Danga, who was arrested two years ago for allegedly insulting the president during an argument with a police officer in a bar.
In May, an opposition activist was jailed for calling Mugabe a "limping donkey" in public.
In August, prosecutors charged a twenty-six-year-old man with his intention to use a poster with Robert Mugabe's face as toilet paper.
The court also declared unconstitutional a law restricting media freedom.
"The state cannot punish people whose statements are later turned out to be false," said Deputy Attorney General Luke Malala.
Until now, Zimbabwean law allowed a person who published false information to be sentenced to twenty years in prison.
"The existence of a law that criminalizes someone for making false statements has a chilling effect on the right to express oneself freely," Malala added.
Despite Mugabe ruling the country with a heavy hand for more than 33 years, Zimbabwe adopted a new constitution with broader civil liberties in March following a referendum.
The country took small steps away from the one-man dictatorship in 2009, when a deal between Mugabe and the opposition propelled Morgan Tsvangiraj to the premiership.
However, the country continues to suffer from the economic crisis and, until 2008, the highest inflation in the world, which exceeded 100,000 percent.
Therefore, in 2009, the government completely abolished the national currency.
Today, in Zimbabwe, only the currencies of other states are used.
The impoverished economy is to Mugabe's imprudent agricultural reform.
In 2000, he redistributed white farmers' land among his supporters and war veterans.
Most of them, however, had no experience with running farms.
