$325 million rescue package for Tasmanian health service
The federal government is insisting that the $325 million rescue package for Tasmania's moribund health system include tough conditions to ensure the state government does not waste funds.
Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek said the Australian Union was taking "urgent action" to avert a crisis caused by the island's ageing population, higher numbers of chronic diseases and systemic disorders.
The funding for four years was decided after government consultations with independent Tasmanian MP Andrew Wilkie.
"The government has come up with an emergency rescue package that we believe will solve the specific problems facing the state," Ms Plibersek said today.
The $325 million package includes $31 million for patient-requested surgeries.
Another 2600 surgeries, including orthopedic and cataract surgeries, will help eliminate indebtedness.
There is also money for free access clinics in Hobart and Launceston, better post-operative care, training of health specialists, mental health services and the introduction of personal electronic health record systems in local hospitals.
"These investments respond to ideas that leading clinicians have told me will best help the Tasmanian healthcare system," Ms Plibersek said.
The Minister stressed that the Tasmanian Government must require a strict reporting and record-keeping regime.
The state will need to maintain the current level of funding to receive the money from the Union of Australia, and report monthly on where the additional funds have been spent.
A three-member committee will be set up to ensure that the state delivers services as efficiently as possible.
Mr Wilkie said today that $325 million will be of no use "until there is genuine reform to lay a more sustainable foundation for Tasmania's public health system".
Still, he praised the government for responding to his request for urgent help, which he first raised in talks with the prime minister in early May.
"I believe the federal aid package can extricate the state's public health service from critical condition," Mr. Wilkie said.
According to the state government, these additional chosen procedures will significantly reverse the recent cuts.
Peter Dutton, a spokesman for the federal opposition on healthcare, believes today's statement is just a "band-aid."
"The reason I'm here is because the Labour government has taken $430 million out of our health system," he told ABC TV.
You cannot have a state government that takes almost half a billion dollars and the Commonwealth of Australia donating 300 million dollars and pretend that this is good news.
Mr Dutton called on Mrs Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar from the rescue package would be spent on higher bureaucracy.
