There will probably be police specialists in the ghettos to ease tensions
In the future, police specialists should work in ghettos in the Czech Republic.
They would spend up to half of their errands here.
They would keep order and solve problems.
Thanks to their knowledge of the environment, they should contribute to reducing tensions between people from poor places and residents from the surrounding area.
In its proposal to reduce security risks, the Ministry of the Interior counts on this.
According to him, the improvement of the situation in the country would be helped mainly by "speeding up the provision of social housing".
The document was discussed by the government.
According to the analysis, there were about 300 poor houses and neighborhoods in the Czech Republic a few years ago.
Some 80,000 people lived there, mainly Roma.
Adults in the ghettos were unemployed, families were dependent on benefits, children ended up in "special" schools.
Usury was rampant.
According to experts, the number of problem localities has increased by a hundred in the meantime.
Relations between their inhabitants and others are becoming more tense.
Anti-Romani marches were held in several places.
The extremists were joined by people from the surrounding area.
According to the Interior Ministry, it is difficult for the police to maintain security and order in areas with ghettos.
An essential condition is "consistent application of equal access in law enforcement".
However, this cannot be achieved without detailed knowledge of the place and people.
A specialist would run errands in the ghetto, where he would spend up to half of his service, the rest would serve in his district.
In a problem locality, he would keep order in order.
He would also know the locals, so he would be better able to solve problems or offenses.
"Thanks to the established trust, specialists will be more easily able to prevent a whole range of unlawful conduct," the ministry said.
Specialists in the ghettos would receive bonuses of 500 to 1,000 crowns per month.
The introduction of special police officers into problem areas is to be covered by Norwegian funds.
The budget is about 600,000 euros (now about 15.5 million crowns).
The Czech Republic pays 15 percent of the amount, funds 85 percent.
Preparations began this year, and a detailed proposal is now being prepared.
The project is to last until 2016.
The authors were inspired by their neighbours.
This mechanism has been successfully applied for several years in Slovakia, where the problem with socially excluded localities is incomparably higher than in the Czech Republic.
"There are so-called Romani settlements here," the report's authors said.
It is not yet clear how many specialists there should be in the Czech Republic.
The answer is to be given by an analysis that identifies places where a special police officer would be needed.
It will also depend on how much money the police will be able to release for these officers each year after the end of the project.
According to the project proposal, the selected police officers will first complete an internship in Slovakia.
Fifty members should undergo this training every year.
From them will emerge the most suitable candidates.
There should also be special education for police officers who will work in the ghettos.
According to the authors, social housing would help to improve the situation.
It should motivate and lead to integration.
According to the ideas of the Interior, it would have three categories.
Hostels with precise rules, such as the number of people per room, would meet the minimum standard.
The middle standard would be in smaller apartments.
Social flats, which would be comparable to ordinary housing, would have a higher standard.
Tenants would have to comply with an integration plan drawn up with them by social workers.
They would have to comply with the accommodation rules, take care of their health, send their children to school, retrain and actively look for work.
If they tried to integrate, they would advance to a higher standard of living.
According to the Interior Ministry, the transitional housing system should operate for at least 30 years until the next generation grows up "in a pro-integration-motivated environment".
The model of social housing is prepared by the ministries for regional development and work.
They have until the end of the year to propose it.
