Minister Holcát renewed the position of Head Nurse for the Czech Republic
The head nurse for the Czech Republic should represent the interests of nurses, whose number in the Czech Republic exceeds 100 thousand.
"I consider it essential that this function is clearly defined and formalized, so that nurses have their representative within the structure of the office - a representative to whom they can always turn if necessary," explained Martin Holcát, Minister of Health.
I appreciate the work of nurses and I think that the field of nursing deserves to be given due attention by the Ministry.
When performing this profession, not only high professional professionalism is needed, but also a human approach and personal conviction.
"I will gladly and responsibly try to promote those steps that can improve the position of nurses."
"We have excellent and skilful nurses in our health service, but I would also like to appeal to those colleagues who do not help us much with their approach to patients, to perform their profession with all empathy and help us improve the image of nurses in the eyes of the public," says Alena Šmídová.
On the occasion of her inauguration, the newly appointed Head Nurse for the Czech Republic, Alena Šmídová, also stated that she wants to deal with various aspects of the nurse's position and intends to cooperate, among other things, with professional associations, professional societies, educators, other non-medical professions and doctors.
"Fundamentally, I do not want to separate the professions of doctors and nurses, but on the contrary, I see them standing side by side, each with their own competencies and, together with other healthcare professionals, forming a well-coordinated working team that provides health services for the benefit of the patient."
"I myself encounter a number of problems that occur in the practice of the profession of nurses, I perceive these difficulties and I intend to participate in their solution."
These include, for example, ensuring the simplification of nursing and medical documentation.
"From my own experience, I know that some administrative tasks unnecessarily burden nurses and take away their time that they could and should rather devote to patients," says Alena Šmídová.
Other areas on which it intends to focus include improving working conditions, finding ways to better mutual cooperation in the team and with the management of health service providers, adjusting competencies and also labor law issues such as compliance with the Labour Code or not overloading nurses with insufficient numbers at a given time and place.
We often hear anonymous complaints, but for fear of possible reprisal, they are not documented in a specific case where the rules could be broken.
"Where there is no prosecutor, there is no judge, and so the function of the Head Nurse of the Czech Republic could serve in this case as a guarantee of maintaining the anonymity of such a complaint and have the specific case examined by the relevant authorities," concludes Alena Šmídová.
Mgr. Alena Šmídová graduated from the Secondary Medical School in the field of Nurse (graduated in 1978) and the Faculty of Arts of Charles University in Prague in the study program Nursing - Pedagogy (graduated in 1992).
Since 2010, he has been the head of the Department of Nursing and Other Non-Medical Disciplines and Recognition of Qualifications at the Department of Education and Science of the Ministry of Health of the Czech Republic.
During her professional career, she worked as a bedside nurse in the internal department, and as a teacher at the Secondary Medical School, where she was the statutory deputy director for 8 years.
