You have to save, young Czechs know.
But most of them do not even know with what interest
More and more Czechs are putting money aside.
However, they do not reach the savings champions in the region.
Austrians save the most money, saving an average of €181 a month.
People in Slovakia also save a little more than Czechs.
These are the results of a survey conducted by the Erste Savings Barometer in the countries of Central and Eastern Europe.
It also showed that savers' mood is improving, with two-thirds planning to set aside more money.
While Czechs are roughly in the middle of the list of savers, in Romania and Serbia people still use very little of their saving products.
For example, almost every second Serb saves "under his pillow" at home, according to the survey.
In the Czech Republic, the number of those who save higher amounts per month has increased this year.
Last year, 26 percent of respondents set aside a thousand to 2,500 crowns every month for various types of savings, this year it is five percent more.
However, the average monthly deposit dropped slightly to CZK 2,078 in a year-on-year comparison.
The biggest hit among savings products is supplementary pension insurance.
This is preferred by 54 percent of Czechs, while three years ago it was the most popular way to increase the value of savings for only 36 percent of people.
On the contrary, the popularity of building savings is declining, and compared to last year, interest in investment funds has also dropped significantly.
Only 16 percent of respondents use them, compared to almost a quarter of people last year.
The survey also showed that although people consider it important to save, most of them do not know what returns they are achieving on individual products.
Especially young people under 30 do not know how their money bears interest.
On the contrary, the oldest group of respondents has the best awareness of the profitability of their deposited money, 73 percent of respondents know it among people over fifty years of age.
In an international comparison of the Erste Group, Czechs lead in the use of online banking, which is regularly used by 44 percent of people.
They are followed by the Slovaks and Austrians with a 12 percent gap.
