Six out of ten companies are preparing for the new Civil Code
Six out of ten companies are intensively preparing for the upcoming effective date of the new Civil Code and the Business Corporations Act on 1 January 2014.
Only eight percent of the business representatives surveyed said that they had not addressed issues related to the two key codes in their company at all.
These are the results of a survey conducted by Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal, which surveyed the opinions of 108 Czech companies.
With the two key codes approaching effective dates, it is only now at the last minute that many managers are beginning to realize how they can have a significant impact on their companies' business.
In our opinion, the biggest changes in private law in the last 50 years will affect all citizens and companies in the Czech Republic.
Because of the manoeuvring of politicians, the business sector lived for a long time in uncertainty about whether or not revolutionary changes would eventually take place.
"However, they now have only a few weeks left to ensure that the transition to the new law takes place without complications for their companies," commented Jan Spáčil, Partner at Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
Of the 61 percent of companies heavily involved in the new codes, 26 percent said their companies had already taken all the necessary measures to be ready in time.
Furthermore, 35 percent of companies of this number plan to take the necessary measures in the near future.
On the other hand, every fifth company has not yet dealt with recodifications, but they still have a specific idea of how to prepare for them.
A total of 11 percent have no opinion and are unable to assess the issue.
Only eight percent of companies admit that they have not yet addressed matters related to recodifications.
The most important legal topic related to the new Civil Code for the largest number of companies surveyed is the conclusion of new contracts (21 percent), followed by the resolution of business conditions (16 percent) and changes in the land register and liability for damage (ten percent each).
In the case of contracts, one of the most important innovations of the entire recodification will take place, namely the unification of the regulation of contracts only within the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in the Civil and Commercial Codes will disappear, as a result of which contract law should become clearer for citizens and entrepreneurs.
"In the case of entrepreneurs, the new regulation will offer many innovations with an emphasis on greater freedom in the arrangement of relationships," said Lukáš Poddaný, attorney-at-law at Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
In connection with the Business Corporations Act, almost a quarter of companies consider the issue of increasing the responsibility of statutory bodies to be the most important topic.
This is followed by topics related to changes in the convening and conduct of general meetings (15 percent) and representation of the company (14 percent).
The new legislation means stricter obligations and possible impacts for statutory bodies, especially in a situation where a company is threatened with bankruptcy or gets into bankruptcy.
"In practice, this means that if members of boards of directors and company executives do not act with due managerial care and do not avert the imminent bankruptcy of the company, they may lose the benefit obtained for the performance of their office only for the last two years," Spáčil added.
NSA revelations increase social paranoia of state surveillance
One peaceful day in late August, a German police helicopter buzzed over the U.S. consulate in Frankfurt, the capital of the German economy.
At the behest of the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution (BfV), Germany's domestic intelligence agency, the purpose of the mission was to take photographs of the roof of the US Advance Patrol, which is located less than 5 km from the European Central Bank and the Bundesbank.
German media say the BfV hoped to be able to identify the presence of eavesdropping antennas, and the action triggered an exchange of views in Berlin between the US and German foreign ministers.
In September, James Clapper, America's director of national intelligence, again insisted that the United States does not use its foreign intelligence capabilities "to steal trade secrets from foreign companies for the benefit of American companies in order to strengthen their international competitiveness or increase their profits."
But ever since Edward Snowden, who went from collaborator to whistleblower, began to reveal his valuable collection of secret surveillance by the United States, European governments and business leaders no longer know whether to believe the director's words.
Following reports that the US National Security Agency spied on a Brazilian oil company and gained access to data held by US cloud providers, including Google and Yahoo, widespread paranoia about state surveillance has reached new heights.
The final straw came with the revelation that Chancellor Angela Merkel's phone had been tapped for perhaps a decade.
If the most powerful person in Europe can be targeted, then surely business leaders are also potential targets.
Snowden has made transparent the intensive cooperation between US intelligence services and companies.
I would say that it is possible that this data is being used for mutual benefit.
"Germany needs to wake up," said Oliver Grün, president of BITMi, which represents small and medium-sized IT companies in Germany.
According to a survey released in July by EY, German companies believe that the US now poses as much risk as China when it comes to industrial espionage and data theft.
However, in all the documentation revealed by Mr. Snowden, there is still no evidence that the United States passed on trade secrets of foreign companies to its own companies.
Policymakers expressed concern that the EU lacks certain IT and internet capabilities and said it should try to reduce its dependence on the US:
Leading entrepreneurs are skeptical of this.
There are voices from the German parliament that we should produce a German Google.
I can just close my eyes and slowly open them again...
This is not the way, says Hasso Plattner, chairman of German software company SAP.
If someone wanted a strong European IT industry, they should not have let them die 20 years ago.
Everything in Germany is subsidized, from coal to cars and farmers.
Everything except the IT industry.
The scale and technical sophistication of the U.S. spy agencies uncovered by Snowden is nonetheless shocking to some companies, who until now thought China posed the greatest surveillance threat.
There is a major turnaround in cloud computing, with European leaders realizing more widely that data stored in the U.S. falls under U.S. jurisdiction and is therefore potentially vulnerable.
According to a survey conducted by the Cloud Security Alliance, about 10 percent of non-U.S. members canceled plans to use a U.S.-based cloud provider after the discovery of the U.S. Prism data mining program.
Jim Snabe, one of SAP's CEOs, says, "We have a new question for customers that wasn't there a year ago – where is my data stored and can you guarantee that it will physically stay in this jurisdiction?"
Many senior German officials argue that the latest reports are just confirmation of what they already knew: that powerful states want to steal their most precious secrets, and that this data must be protected at all costs.
That economic espionage is being carried out is no surprise.
It's always been happening.
"This has been a fundamental topic for many years and has not changed significantly during the current discussion," says Kurt Bock, CEO of the agrochemical company BASF.
The Americans spy on us on a commercial and industrial level, just as we spy on them because it is in our national interest to defend our businesses.
Business leaders are generally reluctant to brag about the countermeasures they've taken to avoid giving the attacker an advantage.
In the case of large companies, it has long been reminded that taking a free USB memory stick at a trade fair or leaving an unprotected laptop in a hotel room is unwise to say the least.
Ulrich Hackenberg, a board member at Audi, says that for many years it has been common practice to collect mobile phones before a board meeting so that they cannot be used as eavesdropping devices.
Germany's BfV advises executives to consider using simple prepaid mobile phones when travelling abroad because of the risk that smartphones may be embezzled.
Prepaid mobile phones are then thrown away.
However, there is concern that SMEs will continue to be vulnerable to hacking and surveillance.
In Germany, many of these companies are global market leaders in their specific areas.
"SMEs often lack the experience, staff and financial resources to effectively protect company secrets against unauthorised access," warns the BfV in its report.
The U.S. warns its own companies against economic espionage by other countries.
According to the Washington Post, in February, the US National Intelligence Estimate listed France in the second line of perpetrators who engage in hacking activities for economic intelligence after China, alongside Russia and Israel.
A board member at Germany's risk-free company concluded that when it comes to economic espionage, "the French are the worst."
Bernard Squarcini, the former head of France's domestic intelligence agency DCRI, said in an interview this month: "The services know perfectly well that all countries, even when they cooperate in the fight against terrorism, spy on their allies."
New nicotine vaccine can take away the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect the mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests need to be done before human trials take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical School in New York says the first signs are good.
"We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome all current approaches," said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry the genetic information to make antinicotinic antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of these antibodies.
Antibodies chase all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
In tests of vaccinated mice that were additionally supplied with nicotine, they continued their normal activities.
But mice that weren't vaccinated "calmed down," the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had gotten into their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be given so often as to maintain adequate levels of antibodies, so they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of the new vaccine should be much lower because they turn liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they feel like trying a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
However, smokers would be much more likely to use it to quit.
"They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not get any benefit from the nicotine vaccine, and this will help them get rid of the habit," he said.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but cautioned that more research was needed.
The Desperate Cry of an Obama Voter
I voted for Obama twice – I shared hope for possible change
He says Obama's sincere efforts have been derailed by the Republican Party's filibuster
Obstructive politics cannot excuse the woes of Obama's health care website or drone strikes
The memoirs of the Obama campaign in 2008 are a sad reminder of what could have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is in his second year of medical school at Harvard.
These days I read a terribly sad book.
This book I thought would encourage me and restore a glimmer of hope during the gloomy days of my sophomore year in medical school.
It's called "The Audacity to Win," and it's a memoir of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patient reviews in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and speeches took your breath away.
The election ended in an overwhelming majority, and television news forced us to reflect on the historical value of the moment.
My classmates wept with joy, and my parents kept the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries headed to the White House, and the nation was ready for change.
At his inauguration in 2008, Obama had 82 percent support.
And here I close the book.
Going to the present is a harsh awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It's hard to remember those optimistic days – they seem distant memories, sad reminders of missed opportunities.
In the years after I cast my first ballot, there were indeed changes.
It was definitely not anything I imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and varied successes – from the Affordable Care Act to the withdrawal of our troops from Iraq, and the end of the "ask no questions, say nothing" policy to the killing of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that partisan obstruction has reversed so many efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, public choice for health care, and the closure of the Guantánamo base, among others.
But after many situations defending the Obama administration from colleagues and comrades, I have reached the absolute limit in terms of the explanations they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political despair.
Republican obstruction cannot explain consent to eavesdropping on foreign leaders or drone strikes that kill innocent children overseas.
They cannot explain the fact that the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans, or that it persecutes those who expose government misconduct.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without due process, or for limiting public contributions and spending during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the report's finding that the White House's efforts to silence the media are "the most aggressive ... from the Nixon administration".
And most recently, they can't even excuse the inability to create a simple website more than 3 years after the Affordable Care Act was signed.
I don't know if this was to be expected.
Whether I should have known at the age of 18 that government power might conflict with the political campaigns that preceded it.
Clearly, elected office does not have a predictable course, and our public conversations will be shaped by the opposition political party and random events such as the Newton massacre.
However, all the examples I have given above appear to be largely the result of the administration's own decision.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unpolished alternative, and seemed unable to consolidate his policies or position.
I felt that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of the next election, would fulfill the hopes we had once heard about.
Yet going back to 2008 – with support for Obama plummeting below 45% this week – is getting harder and harder through this book.
It makes me remember the many promises that have been lost.
This week I read a chapter in the book about how Obama suffered a crushing defeat to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
At an additional meeting during the campaign, he told his staff that they needed to get back up to speed and stay true to their mission.
"I want our magic back," he said.
We must not forget who we are.
Five years have passed, Mr. President, and I totally agree with you.
The ideas expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
