Syria has destroyed its chemical weapons production assets, says watchdog
Syria has destroyed essential equipment for the production of chemical weapons and poison gas munitions, the Committee on Global Chemical Weapons Oversight said on Thursday, as fierce conflicts erupted in the north of the country, near one of the places where poisonous substances are believed to be stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group said more than 120,000 residents had been killed since the start of the civil war nearly three years ago.
The announcement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons came the day before 1 November,
the term set by the Hague-based organisation for Damascus to destroy or disable the operation of all chemical weapons production facilities and chemical mixing machinery for the purpose of generating poisonous gas and refuelling munitions.
The completion of this essentially initial phase of destruction is an important milestone in the ambitious timetable that aims to destroy all Damascus chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of equipment means that Syria will no longer be able to produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus has yet to begin the destruction of existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and sarin nerve gas.
The announcement came as fighting raged Thursday in the town of Safira, which experts say is home to a chemical weapons factory and repositories, the British-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
A group of activists that monitored the total death toll through a network of activists in Syria reported on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 are believed to be civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side has to be 29 954 members of the armed forces of Bashar al-Assad, 18 678 pro-government fighters and 187 militants from the Lebanese Hezbollah.
Among those killed are 2,202 government defectors and some 5,375 opposition fighters, many of whom are foreigners.
On 25 July, the UN estimated that 100,000 people had died in the conflict since March 2011.
Since then, this number has not been updated.
The conflict forced about 2 million people to leave the country.
Assad's forces have been fighting insurgents, many of whom are linked to al-Qaeda, in Safira for weeks.
The observatory said Thursday that casualties were on both sides but did not have specific figures.
The fighting underscored the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors, who face tight deadlines in their mission to rid Syria of its chemical arsenal amid the ongoing civil war.
In a statement from the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, it said his team was now "satisfied that it has verified – and monitored the destruction – Syria's declared critical manufacturing and blending equipment."
He added that "no further inspection activities are planned at this time."
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work, visiting 21 of the 23 sites declared by Damascus.
Inspectors said they were unable to visit two sites due to safety concerns.
On Thursday, the OPCW said the two sites had been "abandoned and ... The chemical weapons program items it contained were moved to two other declared locations that were checked."
It was not immediately clear whether the Safira facility was one of those places that OPCW inspectors could not visit.
