Early puberty: Mature earlier
Research has shown that African-American and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is approaching
It is not proven that hormones or other chemicals are behind it
Experts say that one of the triggers of earlier puberty may be an obesity epidemic.
The trend of earlier puberty is not so noticeable in boys.
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be horrified when her daughter's pubic hair starts growing at 7 or 8 years old?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics' annual conference in Orlando, Florida, this week, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent the new normal.
"I spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that it wasn't usually a sign of rapid progression toward full puberty," Kaplowitz said
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, pubic and armpit hair, and body odour, appear earlier in girls.
Over the past forty years, however, there has been little shift in the age at which menstruation first occurs.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years, up from 12.75 in 1970.
"When breasts start to develop, at least two to three years pass before the first menstruation occurs," said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of "Early puberty in girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem."
The most reliable test of how puberty will progress is time.
It is debated what activates the actual onset of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of 8, the girl is considered "precocious".
In most cases, the process slows down or stops – something pediatricians can monitor closely.
Faster growth may be a reason for the endocrinologist to take tests to rule out serious problems, such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones, which eventually can lead to the cessation of growth and dwarfism in adulthood.
Recommendations on drugs and hormone treatment depend on the age of the child, the speed of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosociological aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication, but acknowledges that "suppressing puberty can alleviate problems with a girl's behavior and her feelings of being different from her peers."
Another big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young daughters to have periods.
"They're worried that she might get pregnant or how she's going to handle hygiene," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she was not prepared emotionally.
She came home from school scared and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
However, there is not yet a coherent body of evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys – like girls – reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz promotes the assumption that the most serious reason is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study on girls ages 6 to 9 that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
The explanations are varied.
From a global perspective, early puberty patterns seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another puzzle: Although boys develop facial and pubic hair at a young age, the trend towards full bloom of early puberty is not as pronounced as it is in girls.
Other physicians attending the American Association of Pediatricians (AAP) conference added further complexities to the topic.
Acne and pubic hair is common even in infants and toddlers.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty," said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get instructions from their child's doctor on how to talk to their child.
"It may mean having to talk to your child sooner than you expect," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, your child is likely to respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that even if it happens prematurely, this process is a normal part of life.
